"content": "<style>\nh1.thlex-title { font-size: 1.3em; margin: 0 0 0.4em; }\n.thlex-key { color: #888; font-size: 0.85em; font-weight: normal; margin-right: 0.4em; }\nnav.thlex-index { margin: 0.5em 0 0.75em; }\nnav.thlex-index ul { margin: 0; padding-left: 1.2em; }\nnav.thlex-index li { margin: 0.15em 0; font-size: 0.95em; }\n.thlex-section { margin: 0.6em 0; }\nh2.thlex-heading { font-size: 1em; margin: 0.5em 0 0.2em; }\nh3.thlex-subheading { font-size: 0.95em; font-weight: normal; font-style: italic; margin: 0.2em 0; }\n.thlex-language-sets { margin: 0.3em 0 0.3em 1em; }\n.thlex-language-set { margin: 0.4em 0; padding-left: 0.75em; border-left: 3px solid #e0e0e0; }\n.thlex-language { font-size: 0.8em; color: #888; margin-right: 0.4em; }\n.thlex-lemma { font-weight: bold; font-family: serif; }\n.thlex-translit { color: #555; font-style: italic; font-size: 0.9em; margin-left: 0.3em; }\n.thlex-refs { font-size: 0.85em; color: #444; margin-top: 0.15em; }\n.thlex-paragraphs p { margin: 0.35em 0; font-size: 0.95em; line-height: 1.5; }\n.thlex-image { margin: 0.5em 0; display: block; }\n.thlex-image img { max-width: 100%; height: auto; display: block; }\nfigcaption.thlex-caption { font-size: 0.85em; color: #555; font-style: italic; margin-top: 0.2em; }\n.thlex-abbr { border-bottom: 1px dotted #888; cursor: help; }\n.thlex-xref { color: #1a5fb4; }\nspan[data-bnType=\"bibleReference\"] { color: #1a5fb4; }\ntable.thlex-table { border-collapse: collapse; font-size: 0.9em; margin: 0.5em 0; }\ntable.thlex-table td { padding: 0.2em 0.6em; vertical-align: top; border: 1px solid #ddd; }\ntable.thlex-table tr:first-child td { font-weight: bold; background: #f5f5f5; }\nul.thlex-index-list { margin: 0.4em 0; padding-left: 1.4em; font-size: 0.95em; line-height: 1.6; }\nul.thlex-index-list ul { margin: 0.1em 0; padding-left: 1.4em; }\n.thlex-index-key { font-weight: bold; font-style: italic; }\n</style><h1 class=\"thlex-title\" id=\"REALIA:1.5.3.3\"><span class=\"thlex-key\">1.5.3.3</span> Weaver’s beam</h1><div class=\"thlex-section\">\n<h2 class=\"thlex-heading\">References:</h2>\n<div class=\"thlex-language-sets\">\n<div class=\"thlex-language-set\">\n<span class=\"thlex-language\">Hebrew</span> <span class=\"thlex-lemma\">מָנוֹר, ארג</span> <span class=\"thlex-translit\">(mnor ’orgim)</span>\n<div class=\"thlex-refs\"><a href=\"https://ref.ly/1Sam17:7\">1SA 17:7</a>, <a href=\"https://ref.ly/2Sam21:19\">2SA 21:19</a>, <a href=\"https://ref.ly/1Chr11:23\">1CH 11:23</a>, <a href=\"https://ref.ly/1Chr20:5\">1CH 20:5</a></div>\n</div>\n<div class=\"thlex-language-set\">\n<span class=\"thlex-language\">Greek</span> <span class=\"thlex-lemma\">ἱστός</span> <span class=\"thlex-translit\">(histos)</span>\n<div class=\"thlex-refs\"><a href=\"https://ref.ly/Odes11:12\">ODA 11:12</a></div>\n</div>\n</div>\n</div><div class=\"thlex-section\">\n<h2 class=\"thlex-heading\">Description:</h2>\n<div class=\"thlex-paragraphs\">\n<p>\n            <figure class=\"thlex-image\"><img class=\"thlex-img\" src=\"images/WEB-0346_loom_en.jpg\" alt=\"Vertical loom\"><figcaption class=\"thlex-caption\">Vertical loom (© CristianChirita, CC BY-SA 3.0, via Wikimedia Commons)</figcaption></figure>The weaver’s beam was a wooden rod approximately 5–6 centimeters (2–2.5 inches) in diameter. The length could vary. Around this beam the warp threads were attached, and the cloth was rolled on it as it grew in length.</p>\n<hr/>\n</div>\n</div><div class=\"thlex-section\">\n<h2 class=\"thlex-heading\">Usage:</h2>\n<div class=\"thlex-paragraphs\">\n<p>See <a class=\"thlex-xref\" data-bnType=\"lexiconLink\" data-collection=\"\" data-key=\"\" href=\"#\">1.5.3 Cloth manufacture&lt;REALIA:1.5.3&gt;</a>.</p>\n<hr/>\n</div>\n</div><div class=\"thlex-section\">\n<h2 class=\"thlex-heading\">Translation:</h2>\n<div class=\"thlex-paragraphs\">\n<p>In the Old Testament references, it is the exceptional size of each giant’s spear that is in focus. In <a href=\"https://ref.ly/1Sam17:7\">1SA 17:7</a><abbr class=\"thlex-abbr\" title=\"Contemporary English Version\">CEV</abbr> has taken into account that weaving on a hand loom is little known today in western English-speaking countries, so it has omitted reference to the weaver’s beam by saying “and his spear was so big ….” Where hand weaving is not commonly known, translators may want to follow this pattern. Another possible model is “and the shaft of his spear was twice as thick as an ordinary spear ….”</p>\n<p>The Greek word <em>histos</em> in <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Odes11:12\">ODA 11:12</a> may refer to either the beam or the entire loom. It is usually not necessary to render this word literally; compare <abbr class=\"thlex-abbr\" title=\"New Revised Standard Version (1989)\">NRSV</abbr> “a piece she had woven” or <abbr class=\"thlex-abbr\" title=\"New Jerusalem Bible (1985)\">NJB</abbr> “a piece of work.”</p>\n</div>\n</div>",
